  "text": "Nuclear medicine imaging techniques such as [CITATION_1] F-FDG positron emission tomography (PET) and single photon emission computerized tomography (SPECT) have been used to differentiate recurrent glioma from radiation injury; however, the results have been controversial and inconclusive [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . PET and SPECT have limited spatial resolution and relatively high cortical background activity, therefore, [CITATION_4] F-FDG-PET cannot accurately delineate residual tumor after therapy [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Moreover, [CITATION_7] F-FDG-PET images also need co-registration with MRI or CT images to differentiate small or suspicious lesions. In contrast, [CITATION_8] C-MET-PET is better suited for monitoring the effects of radiation therapy where injury is displayed as a reduction of the relative methionine-uptake. Nonetheless, the short half-life of [CITATION_9] C is still considered a significant limitation to the widespread use of this technique [CITATION_10] .",
